# Conda Environment - chili-env

For this project (CHILI products), **always use the conda environment `chili-env`** for:

- Installing Python packages (e.g. `pip install`, new dependencies)
- Running scripts (e.g. `python scripts/brain_worker.py`, `uvicorn`)
- Running tests

## Commands

```powershell
# Activate first (if not already)
conda activate chili-env

# Install from requirements
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Install a new package
pip install <package>

# Run the app (server rule uses chili-env or direct uvicorn after activate)
uvicorn app.main:app ...
```

When suggesting installs or terminal commands that run Python, assume `chili-env` is the active environment or use `conda run -n chili-env ...` if the shell may not have it activated.
